### Why cursor-based pagination is superior for this use case

- **No expensive `COUNT(*)`**: The original query scanned the entire table (or index) just to compute totals. On large or growing tables this is slow and becomes a bottleneck. Cursor pagination removes it entirely.
- **Correctness under concurrency**: OFFSET pagination is unstable. New rows inserted earlier in the result set (or deletions) between requests cause duplicates or skipped items ("page drift"). The `(created_at, id)` cursor gives a stable position in the ordered set.
- **Performance at depth**: `OFFSET 50000 LIMIT 20` forces the database to read and discard 50,000 rows. A cursor uses an index seek on the `(created_at, id)` columns and only fetches the needed rows — dramatically faster for deep/infinite-scroll use cases.
- **Simpler and more scalable**: The N+1 fetch + `hasMore`/`nextCursor` pattern is ideal for modern frontends (infinite scroll, "Load more") and works efficiently even when the table has millions of rows, provided an index exists on `(created_at DESC, id DESC)` (or a covering index).

The cursor is intentionally opaque (base64-encoded JSON) so clients treat it as a black box and the internal representation can evolve later without breaking API contracts.
